CFItems.fullStatement: Circles

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Understand and apply theorems about circles

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Prove that all circles are similar.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Identify and describe relationships among inscribed angles, radii, and chords.
CFItems.notes: Include the relationship between central, inscribed, and circumscribed angles; inscribed angles on a diameter are right angles; the radius of a circle is perpendicular to the tangent where the radius intersects the circle.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Construct the inscribed and circumscribed circles of a triangle, and prove properties of angles for a quadrilateral inscribed in a circle.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Construct a tangent line from a point outside a given circle to the circle.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Find arc lengths and areas of sectors of circles

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Derive using similarity the fact that the length of the arc intercepted by an angle is proportional to the radius, and define the radian measure of the angle as the constant of proportionality; derive the formula for the area of a sector.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Expressing Geometric Properties with Equations

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Translate between the geometric description and the equation for a conic section

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Derive the equation of a circle of given center and radius using the Pythagorean Theorem; complete the square to find the center and radius of a circle given by an equation.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Derive the equation of a parabola given a focus and directrix.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Derive the equations of ellipses and hyperbolas given the foci, using the fact that the sum or difference of distances from the foci is constant.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use coordinates to prove simple geometric theorems algebraically

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use coordinates to prove simple geometric theorems algebraically. *For example, prove or disprove that a figure defined by four given points in the coordinate plane is a rectangle; prove or disprove that the point $(1, \sqrt{3})$ lies on the circle centered at the origin and containing the point (0, 2).*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Prove the slope criteria for parallel and perpendicular lines and use them to solve geometric problems (e.g., find the equation of a line parallel or perpendicular to a given line that passes through a given point).

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Find the point on a directed line segment between two given points that partitions the segment in a given ratio.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use coordinates to compute perimeters of polygons and areas of triangles and rectangles, e.g., using the distance formula.

CFItems.fullStatement: Geometric Measurement & Dimension

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Explain volume formulas and use them to solve problems

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Give an informal argument for the formulas for the circumference of a circle, area of a circle, volume of a cylinder, pyramid, and cone.
CFItems.notes: Use dissection arguments, Cavalieri's principle, and informal limit arguments.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Give an informal argument using Cavalieri's principle for the formulas for the volume of a sphere and other solid figures.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use volume formulas for cylinders, pyramids, cones, and spheres to solve problems.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Visualize relationships between two-dimensional and three-dimensional objects

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Identify the shapes of two-dimensional cross-sections of three-dimensional objects, and identify three-dimensional objects generated by rotations of two-dimensional objects.

CFItems.fullStatement: Apply geometric concepts in modeling situations

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use geometric shapes, their measures, and their properties to describe objects (e.g., modeling a tree trunk or a human torso as a cylinder).
CFItems.notes: Modeling is best interpreted not as a collection of isolated topics but in relation to other standards. CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Apply concepts of density based on area and volume in modeling situations (e.g., persons per square mile, BTUs per cubic foot).

The star symbol sometimes appears on the heading for a group of standards; in that case, it should be understood to apply to all standards in that group.

CFItems.fullStatement: Apply geometric methods to solve design problems (e.g., designing an object or structure to satisfy physical constraints or minimize cost; working with typographic grid systems based on ratios).

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Interpreting Categorical & Quantitative Data

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Summarize, represent, and interpret data on a single count or measurement variable

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Represent data with plots on the real number line (dot plots, histograms, and box plots).

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use statistics appropriate to the shape of the data distribution to compare center (median, mean) and spread (interquartile range, standard deviation) of two or more different data sets.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Interpret differences in shape, center, and spread in the context of the data sets, accounting for possible effects of extreme data points (outliers).

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use the mean and standard deviation of a data set to fit it to a normal distribution and to estimate population percentages. Recognize that there are data sets for which such a procedure is not appropriate. Use calculators, spreadsheets, and tables to estimate areas under the normal curve.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Summarize, represent, and interpret data on two categorical and quantitative variables

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Summarize categorical data for two categories in two-way frequency tables. Interpret relative frequencies in the context of the data (including joint, marginal, and conditional relative frequencies). Recognize possible associations and trends in the data.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Represent data on two quantitative variables on a scatter plot, and describe how the variables are related.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Fit a function to the data; use functions fitted to data to solve problems in the context of the data.
CFItems.notes: Use given functions or choose a function suggested by the context. Emphasize linear, quadratic, and exponential models.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Informally assess the fit of a function by plotting and analyzing residuals.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Fit a linear function for a scatter plot that suggests a linear association.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Interpret linear models

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Interpret the slope (rate of change) and the intercept (constant term) of a linear model in the context of the data.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Compute (using technology) and interpret the correlation coefficient of a linear fit.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Distinguish between correlation and causation.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Making Inferences & Justifying Conclusions

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Understand and evaluate random processes underlying statistical experiments

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Understand statistics as a process for making inferences about population parameters based on a random sample from that population.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Decide if a specified model is consistent with results from a given data-generating process, e.g., using simulation. *For example, a model says a spinning coin falls heads up with probability 0.5. Would a result of 5 tails in a row cause you to question the model?*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Make inferences and justify conclusions from sample surveys, experiments, and observational studies

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Recognize the purposes of and differences among sample surveys, experiments, and observational studies; explain how randomization relates to each.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use data from a sample survey to estimate a population mean or proportion; develop a margin of error through the use of simulation models for random sampling.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use data from a randomized experiment to compare two treatments; use simulations to decide if differences between parameters are significant.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Evaluate reports based on data.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Conditional Probability & the Rules of Probability

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Understand independence and conditional probability and use them to interpret data

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Describe events as subsets of a sample space (the set of outcomes) using characteristics (or categories) of the outcomes, or as unions, intersections, or complements of other events ("or," "and," "not").

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Understand that two events A and B are independent if the probability of A and B occurring together is the product of their probabilities, and use this characterization to determine if they are independent.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Understand the conditional probability of A given B as $\frac{P(A and B)}{P(B)}$, and interpret independence of A and B as saying that the conditional probability of A given B is the same as the probability of A, and the conditional probability of B given A is the same as the probability of B.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Construct and interpret two-way frequency tables of data when two categories are associated with each object being classified. Use the two-way table as a sample space to decide if events are independent and to approximate conditional probabilities. *For example, collect data from a random sample of students in your school on their favorite subject among math, science, and English. Estimate the probability that a randomly selected student from your school will favor science given that the student is in tenth grade. Do the same for other subjects and compare the results.*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Recognize and explain the concepts of conditional probability and independence in everyday language and everyday situations. *For example, compare the chance of having lung cancer if you are a smoker with the chance of being a smoker if you have lung cancer.*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use the rules of probability to compute probabilities of compound events in a uniform probability model

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Find the conditional probability of A given B as the fraction of B's outcomes that also belong to A, and interpret the answer in terms of the model.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Apply the Addition Rule, P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B), and interpret the answer in terms of the model.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Apply the general Multiplication Rule in a uniform probability model, P(A and B) = P(A)P(B|A) = P(B)P(A|B), and interpret the answer in terms of the model.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Use permutations and combinations to compute probabilities of compound events and solve problems.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Using Probability to Make Decisions

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Calculate expected values and use them to solve problems

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Define a random variable for a quantity of interest by assigning a numerical value to each event in a sample space; graph the corresponding probability distribution using the same graphical displays as for data distributions.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Calculate the expected value of a random variable; interpret it as the mean of the probability distribution.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Develop a probability distribution for a random variable defined for a sample space in which theoretical probabilities can be calculated; find the expected value. *For example, find the theoretical probability distribution for the number of correct answers obtained by guessing on all five questions of a multiple-choice test where each question has four choices, and find the expected grade under various grading schemes.*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Develop a probability distribution for a random variable defined for a sample space in which probabilities are assigned empirically; find the expected value. *For example, find a current data distribution on the number of TV sets per household in the United States, and calculate the expected number of sets per household. How many TV sets would you expect to find in 100 randomly selected households?*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Use probability to evaluate outcomes of decisions

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Weigh the possible outcomes of a decision by assigning probabilities to payoff values and finding expected values.

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Find the expected payoff for a game of chance. *For example, find the expected winnings from a state lottery ticket or a game at a fast-food restaurant.*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: Evaluate and compare strategies on the basis of expected values. *For example, compare a high-deductible versus a low-deductible automobile insurance policy using various, but reasonable, chances of having a minor or a major accident.*

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Use probabilities to make fair decisions (e.g., drawing by lots, using a random number generator).

CFDocumentURI.title: Common Core State Standards for Math

CFItems.fullStatement: (+) Analyze decisions and strategies using probability concepts (e.g., product testing, medical testing, pulling a hockey goalie at the end of a game).
